head.title: Decay on several sorts of heterogeneous centers: Special monodisperse approximation in the situation of strong unsymmetry. 4. Numerical results for the approximation of essential asymptotes

article.h1: Decay on several sorts of heterogeneous centers: Special monodisperse approximation in the situation of strong unsymmetry. 4. Numerical results for the approximation of essential asymptotes

div.p: This manuscript directly continues [1], [2], [3]. All definitions and formulas have to be taken from [1]. The numerical results for comparison with the total monodisperse approximation has to be taken from [2]. The numerical results for the floating monodisperse approximation can be taken from [3].
We have to recall again the system of the condensation equations. It can be written in the following form

div.p: This approximation will be called as ”approximation of essential asymptotes”. The real advantage of this approximation is the absence of the exponential nonlinearity. When this approximation will be introduced into equation on the parameters of the condensation process there will be no numerical difficulties to solve it.

We have tried all mentioned approximations for b𝑏italic-bb from 0.20.2NUMBER:0.20.2 up to 5.25.2NUMBER:5.25.2 with the step 0.20.2NUMBER:0.20.2 and for l𝑙italic-ll from 0.20.2NUMBER:0.20.2 up to 5.25.2NUMBER:5.25.2 with a step 0.20.2NUMBER:0.20.2. We calculate the relative error in N𝑁italic-NN. The results are drawn in fig.1 for NCsubscript𝑁𝐶italic-N POSTSUBSCRIPT:start italic-C POSTSUBSCRIPT:endN_{C} where the relative errors are marked by r3subscript𝑟3italic-r POSTSUBSCRIPT:start NUMBER:3 POSTSUBSCRIPT:endr_{3}.

We see that the relative errors of NBsubscript𝑁𝐵italic-N POSTSUBSCRIPT:start italic-B POSTSUBSCRIPT:endN_{B} and NCsubscript𝑁𝐶italic-N POSTSUBSCRIPT:start italic-C POSTSUBSCRIPT:endN_{C} are very small and practically the same. One can not find the difference between fig.1 in [3] and fig.1 here.

The maximum of errors in NBsubscript𝑁𝐵italic-N POSTSUBSCRIPT:start italic-B POSTSUBSCRIPT:endN_{B} and NCsubscript𝑁𝐶italic-N POSTSUBSCRIPT:start italic-C POSTSUBSCRIPT:endN_{C} lies near l=0𝑙0italic-l RELOP:equals NUMBER:0l=0. So, we have to analyse the situation with small values of l𝑙italic-ll. It was done in fig.2 for NCsubscript𝑁𝐶italic-N POSTSUBSCRIPT:start italic-C POSTSUBSCRIPT:endN_{C}. We see that we can not find the maximum error because it increases at small b𝑏italic-bb. Then we have to calculate the situation with b=0𝑏0italic-b RELOP:equals NUMBER:0b=0. The results are shown in fig.3. One can see one curve with two wings. The upper wing corresponds to the error of NAsubscript𝑁𝐴italic-N POSTSUBSCRIPT:start italic-A POSTSUBSCRIPT:endN_{A} and the lower corresponds to the relative error in NBsubscript𝑁𝐵italic-N POSTSUBSCRIPT:start italic-B POSTSUBSCRIPT:endN_{B} and NCsubscript𝑁𝐶italic-N POSTSUBSCRIPT:start italic-C POSTSUBSCRIPT:endN_{C}. At l=0𝑙0italic-l RELOP:equals NUMBER:0l=0 these wings come together. We see that our hypothesis (the worst situation for the floating monodisperse approximation takes place when the first type heterogeneous centers are unexhausted) is really true.

The worst situation is when b𝑏italic-bb is near zero and l𝑙italic-ll lies also near zero. Here we can use the total monodisperse approximation to estimate the error. It is clear that the relative error in NAsubscript𝑁𝐴italic-N POSTSUBSCRIPT:start italic-A POSTSUBSCRIPT:endN_{A} is greater than in NBsubscript𝑁𝐵italic-N POSTSUBSCRIPT:start italic-B POSTSUBSCRIPT:endN_{B} (not in NCsubscript𝑁𝐶italic-N POSTSUBSCRIPT:start italic-C POSTSUBSCRIPT:endN_{C}). So, we can calculate r1subscript𝑟1italic-r POSTSUBSCRIPT:start NUMBER:1 POSTSUBSCRIPT:endr_{1}, see that when b𝑏italic-bb goes to zero it decreases (it is clear also from the physical reasons) and estimate the error r2subscript𝑟2italic-r POSTSUBSCRIPT:start NUMBER:2 POSTSUBSCRIPT:endr_{2} at b=0𝑏0italic-b RELOP:equals NUMBER:0b=0, l=0𝑙0italic-l RELOP:equals NUMBER:0l=0 by R1subscript𝑅1italic-R POSTSUBSCRIPT:start NUMBER:1 POSTSUBSCRIPT:endR_{1} calculated at small b𝑏italic-bb and l=0𝑙0italic-l RELOP:equals NUMBER:0l=0. Then one can see that it is small.

An interesting problem is to see whether NBsubscript𝑁𝐵italic-N POSTSUBSCRIPT:start italic-B POSTSUBSCRIPT:endN_{B} and NCsubscript𝑁𝐶italic-N POSTSUBSCRIPT:start italic-C POSTSUBSCRIPT:endN_{C} are different or no. Earlier we can not see the difference. In fig.4 one can see the ratio r2/r3subscript𝑟2subscript𝑟3italic-r POSTSUBSCRIPT:start NUMBER:2 POSTSUBSCRIPT:end MULOP:divide italic-r POSTSUBSCRIPT:start NUMBER:3 POSTSUBSCRIPT:endr_{2}/r_{3} plotted at b=0𝑏0italic-b RELOP:equals NUMBER:0b=0 and can note that only for l≈0.01÷0.02𝑙0.010.02italic-l RELOP:approximately-equals NUMBER:0.01 MULOP:divide NUMBER:0.02l\approx 0.01\div 0.02 one can see the small difference. It means that to see the difference between these approximations the ratio between the scale of the first type centers nucleation and the scale of the second type centers nucleation must be giant. Even at giant values the difference is small.
